    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-28T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-28T04:00:00-05:00" n="1016"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1016">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163/1020: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The First Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-28T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 28, 1940—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 28—4:56 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>493. Peiping’s 492, November 28, 4 p.m.<note n="51" xml:id="d1016fn51">Not
                        printed.</note> newspaper attack on mission schools. The Embassy believes
                    the editorial quoted in the telegram under reference represents the ideas of the
                    Japanese military who in Japan, Korea and Manchuria have undermined the
                    integrity of mission-operated schools not only because such schools were under
                        <pb facs="0918" n="910" xml:id="pg_910"/> foreign influence, but also
                    because they formed centers of liberal and democratic thought. Such concepts are
                    naturally anathema to the Japanese ultra nationalists who seem determined to
                    extirpate all opposition to their ideas of the state and of society.</p>
                <p>It is possible that the editorial coming at this particular time of international
                    strain is the opening gun in a campaign to attempt the eradication or at least
                    the lessening of foreign influence in the educational system of North China.</p>
                <p>Sent to Department, repeated to Chungking, Tientsin. By air mail to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smyth</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
